    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i've been seeing these intermittent \"Connection Reset by Peer\" errors in our production EC2 instances on AWS. it's not constant, just happens every few hours. \n\nhere's a snippet from the CloudWatch logs:\n2023-10-27T14:22:01Z ERROR [connection-handler] remote peer closed connection unexpectedly: Connection reset by peer (errno: 104)\n2023-10-27T14:25:44Z ERROR [connection-handler] remote peer closed connection unexpectedly: Connection reset by peer (errno: 104)\n\ncould this be an issue with our security group configs or something else in the VPC setup?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error, especially intermittently, is often not a direct security group misconfiguration, but rather a signaling issue on the other end of the connection. This frequently suggests that the remote peer (the client or upstream service) is abruptly closing the socket due to timeouts, resource constraints, or application-level errors. You should investigate the application logs on both the EC2 instance and the service it is connecting to, as the problem likely lies in how the established TCP session is being managed.",
      "source": "target",
