    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i checked the application logs on the client side and they don't show any specific reason for the disconnect, it just looks like the socket drops. \n\ncould it be a network-level thing like an idle timeout in the NAT gateway or an NLB? i'm worried it might be a race condition or some weird packet dropping happening in the VPC. any ideas on how to isolate if it's infrastructure vs the code?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Idle timeouts on infrastructure components like NAT Gateways or Network Load Balancers (NLB) are definitely a strong possibility if the connection is simply timing out without an application message. To isolate this, you can try running a simple, non-application-dependent network test between the two endpoints to see if the reset persists. If the issue vanishes when using a basic tool like `ping` or `telnet` for sustained periods, it points strongly toward the connection application layer. If the reset happens even during basic connectivity tests, you might need to check packet capture tools like `tcpdump` on the EC2 instance to see exactly *when* the RST packet is arriving.",
      "source": "target",
